1
00:00:09,600 --> 00:00:11,320
The Truth Teller was nominated

2
00:00:11,360 --> 00:00:13,880
in this year's
Ohio Journalism Awards.

3
00:00:13,920 --> 00:00:15,120
You heard right.
The Truth Teller.

4
00:00:15,160 --> 00:00:16,640
Three times, in fact.

5
00:00:16,680 --> 00:00:20,000
Mare for her great story
on the Softees clog,

6
00:00:20,040 --> 00:00:21,920
Ned for The Truth Teller itself,

7
00:00:21,960 --> 00:00:25,800
and a fresh-faced new upstart,
heh, named Oscar Martinez

8
00:00:25,840 --> 00:00:29,360
for the Mr. Digit Puzzle.
Best New Game.

9
00:00:29,400 --> 00:00:33,760
I can't remember the last time
The Truth Teller won something.

10
00:00:33,800 --> 00:00:34,800
Thank you, thank you.

11
00:00:34,840 --> 00:00:36,640
I'd like to say this means a lot,

12
00:00:36,680 --> 00:00:41,600
but all it represents really
is a year of backbreaking,

13
00:00:41,640 --> 00:00:42,720
liver-destroying work

14
00:00:42,760 --> 00:00:44,520
that nearly put me in the hospital.

15
00:00:44,560 --> 00:00:46,480
- Hey, Ned.
- How you doing?

16
00:00:46,520 --> 00:00:49,200
- Did you meet my husband?
- Luke Putnam.

17
00:00:49,240 --> 00:00:50,240
- Oh!
- My brother.

18
00:00:50,280 --> 00:00:52,880
Yes! Yes, yes. I see
the resemblance. Very cool.

19
00:00:52,920 --> 00:00:55,000
You didn't bring someone
for, uh, moral support?

20
00:00:55,040 --> 00:00:56,880
God, no, no.
I don't need any moral support.

21
00:00:56,920 --> 00:00:58,880
You only need support
if you care about winning.

22
00:00:58,920 --> 00:01:01,720
- Not a big deal either way.
- Mm.

23
00:01:01,760 --> 00:01:03,440
What is not a big deal?

24
00:01:03,480 --> 00:01:05,440
- Oh, my God.
- Whoa.

25
00:01:05,480 --> 00:01:09,280
Uh, winning. I don't think
winning's a big deal.

26
00:01:09,320 --> 00:01:10,520
- Spinning?
- Winning.

27
00:01:10,560 --> 00:01:11,560
Oh, you really said winning.

28
00:01:11,600 --> 00:01:12,600
I did, yeah.

29
00:01:12,640 --> 00:01:14,960
That's bullshit.
Winning's always better.

30
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:16,080
I don't think it is.

31
00:01:16,120 --> 00:01:18,680
I think sometimes
it's actually worse.

32
00:01:18,720 --> 00:01:19,960
How?

33
00:01:20,120 --> 00:01:24,840
Well, if you need validation
from strangers...

34
00:01:25,039 --> 00:01:28,480
Is that a rabbit's foot
in your hand?

35
00:01:28,520 --> 00:01:30,120
No, no. This is, um...

36
00:01:30,840 --> 00:01:36,000
It's part of a dead mouse
I found in the street. So...

37
00:01:36,039 --> 00:01:39,160
It's not a mouse
and it's not a rabbit's foot.

38
00:01:39,200 --> 00:01:42,360
I cut the leg off
my childhood stuffed animal

39
00:01:42,400 --> 00:01:45,720
so that I can rub it
whenever I want.

40
00:01:45,759 --> 00:01:46,759
I mean, it's possible

41
00:01:46,800 --> 00:01:49,520
my subconscious
has some desire for awards,

42
00:01:49,560 --> 00:01:50,920
'cause I dream about it constantly

43
00:01:50,960 --> 00:01:53,840
but as long as I shove
that desire back down

44
00:01:53,880 --> 00:01:55,680
when I wake up...

45
00:01:56,200 --> 00:01:57,759
everything's fine.

46
00:01:57,800 --> 00:01:59,759
Oh, look! Mare's here!

47
00:02:00,280 --> 00:02:01,760
And her date.

48
00:02:02,160 --> 00:02:03,440
Ah.

49
00:02:03,600 --> 00:02:06,320
I hope they have a pleasant evening.

50
00:02:34,760 --> 00:02:36,920
Summer and I
really needed this.

51
00:02:36,960 --> 00:02:38,920
Oscar gave me his plus one
and all I had to do

52
00:02:38,960 --> 00:02:41,920
was promise to match
his purchase orders to invoices

53
00:02:41,960 --> 00:02:43,000
for the entire month of July.

54
00:02:43,040 --> 00:02:47,800
But like, July's weeks away.
And look at that woman go.

55
00:02:47,840 --> 00:02:49,600
What?

56
00:02:49,640 --> 00:02:52,240
- You look beautiful, sweetie.
- Thank you so much!

57
00:02:52,280 --> 00:02:54,120
- Good to see you too.
- No. You?

58
00:02:54,160 --> 00:02:55,160
- Me too? Okay.
- Yes!

59
00:02:55,280 --> 00:02:56,800
There's Marv's table.
Social summit.

60
00:02:58,280 --> 00:03:00,080
We should be here.

61
00:03:00,200 --> 00:03:03,000
- Nate, glad you could make it.
- Oh, thank you.

62
00:03:03,040 --> 00:03:04,040
- Oh, careful!
- Uh, sorry!

63
00:03:04,080 --> 00:03:05,720
- Sober one month.
- Bravest man I know.

64
00:03:05,760 --> 00:03:08,480
- Congrats.
- I'm very proud of this.

65
00:03:08,800 --> 00:03:10,640
Gave the guy
a bottle of whiskey for it.

66
00:03:10,680 --> 00:03:12,360
- Hello, everybody.
- Hello, everybody.

67
00:03:12,400 --> 00:03:13,680
- Hi.
- Hi, Oscar.

68
00:03:13,720 --> 00:03:16,360
I'm sorry, I think
you're at the wrong table.

69
00:03:16,400 --> 00:03:17,760
Table 14.

70
00:03:17,800 --> 00:03:21,440
Right, I'm sorry.
Fifteen, but we should be 14.

71
00:03:21,480 --> 00:03:22,720
Fifteen's over there.

72
00:03:22,800 --> 00:03:23,960
Aww!

73
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:25,240
Is that a joke?

74
00:03:25,280 --> 00:03:26,400
Is that somebody's funny joke?

75
00:03:26,440 --> 00:03:31,200
Wowee. Making it look like
we're at the kids' table.

76
00:03:31,240 --> 00:03:33,120
Maybe because I look so young.

77
00:03:33,160 --> 00:03:34,560
- It's not that.
- No.

78
00:03:34,600 --> 00:03:36,040
I mean...

79
00:03:38,160 --> 00:03:39,680
- Okay.
- Oh...

80
00:03:39,720 --> 00:03:42,480
- Mommy, Daddy.
- Mommy.

81
00:03:42,520 --> 00:03:44,200
- Hi!
- Hi!

82
00:03:44,240 --> 00:03:46,480
What are you doing here?

83
00:03:46,520 --> 00:03:47,960
Well, we thought
we'd bring them down

84
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:49,840
to say goodnight to you guys.

85
00:03:49,880 --> 00:03:51,640
We already said goodnight.

86
00:03:51,680 --> 00:03:53,079
They wanted to again.

87
00:03:53,120 --> 00:03:54,640
Oh, did you?

88
00:03:54,680 --> 00:03:56,800
Okay, well, you guys are gonna go

89
00:03:56,840 --> 00:03:59,520
with your Uncle Travis
and Auntie Adelola.

90
00:03:59,560 --> 00:04:00,560
- Aah...
- Ugh!

91
00:04:00,680 --> 00:04:02,240
Head back... Back, okay?

92
00:04:02,280 --> 00:04:03,480
- What a night.
- Yes.

93
00:04:03,520 --> 00:04:05,600
What a night.

94
00:04:05,640 --> 00:04:07,480
Have you two met my father?

95
00:04:08,880 --> 00:04:10,880
Oh, Jesus wept.

96
00:04:10,920 --> 00:04:13,120
Oh, my God. Are you kidding me?

97
00:04:13,160 --> 00:04:17,600
Dude. Is it... Man!
You absolutely rock, dude.

98
00:04:17,640 --> 00:04:19,000
It's nice to meet you.

99
00:04:19,040 --> 00:04:21,480
Theo rolls coal.
I follow him on YouTube.

100
00:04:21,519 --> 00:04:25,040
You get a diesel truck,
you take off the carburetor,

101
00:04:25,080 --> 00:04:27,160
you lock the brakes, you floor it,

102
00:04:27,200 --> 00:04:28,240
and all this black smoke...

103
00:04:28,280 --> 00:04:32,280
- Hello, hello.
- ...goes everywhere.

104
00:04:32,320 --> 00:04:33,320
Isn't that cool?

105
00:04:33,360 --> 00:04:35,360
It's very bad for the environment.

106
00:04:35,400 --> 00:04:37,080
I cannot believe I just met Theo.

107
00:04:37,120 --> 00:04:39,159
Mare, put a ring
on that thing, for real.

108
00:04:39,200 --> 00:04:41,480
All right, Travis,
no one needs to know

109
00:04:41,520 --> 00:04:43,960
about your backwoods viewing habits.

110
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:45,760
No offense, you can go to bed.

111
00:04:45,800 --> 00:04:48,040
- Okay.
- See you tomorrow.

112
00:04:48,080 --> 00:04:50,520
Do I think Ned is a little jealous?

113
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:54,960
I don't know.

114
00:05:00,640 --> 00:05:03,920
Hey, isn't that the girl
you're dating?

115
00:05:04,560 --> 00:05:07,280
The weather girl
you're hooking up with?

116
00:05:07,320 --> 00:05:08,360
- Oh!
- Uh-oh!

117
00:05:08,400 --> 00:05:10,320
Is your whole rotation here?

118
00:05:10,640 --> 00:05:13,000
Yeah, yeah.
It's Gloria Tornado.

119
00:05:13,040 --> 00:05:16,200
She's hot.
Are you gonna say hi?

120
00:05:16,480 --> 00:05:18,760
"Hi" would be pretty tame for us.

121
00:05:18,800 --> 00:05:21,280
I'm gonna say a lot more
than "hi" tomorrow.

122
00:05:21,320 --> 00:05:22,480
Yeah, yeah. If I start it,

123
00:05:22,520 --> 00:05:24,000
it's not gonna stop at "hi,"
believe me.

124
00:05:24,080 --> 00:05:27,840
Okay.
Well, maybe I'll go say hello.

125
00:05:27,880 --> 00:05:32,000
And, um,
we can compare notes on you.

126
00:05:32,360 --> 00:05:33,840
Mm?

127
00:05:37,159 --> 00:05:38,480
Good evening,

128
00:05:38,520 --> 00:05:41,960
and welcome to the 63rd
Annual Excellence Awards

129
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:44,480
of the Ohio Press Association.

130
00:05:49,040 --> 00:05:51,560
I heard the chef is from Chicago.

131
00:05:51,600 --> 00:05:55,000
How exciting is this evening, right?

132
00:05:55,040 --> 00:05:57,520
Yes, it's good to be back.

133
00:05:57,560 --> 00:06:00,480
It's been a few years.
Hasn't it?

134
00:06:00,520 --> 00:06:01,920
...to turn our eyes away

135
00:06:01,960 --> 00:06:03,240
from the broader world around us.

136
00:06:03,280 --> 00:06:06,840
I need to distance myself
from Esmeralda.

137
00:06:06,880 --> 00:06:10,560
I'm getting swept away
in her mediocrity.

138
00:06:10,600 --> 00:06:14,080
A prestige shift is happening.

139
00:06:14,120 --> 00:06:18,600
Oscar now has the ear of Marv
and that is a dangerous thing.

140
00:06:18,640 --> 00:06:23,280
Accountants have a nasty habit
of getting rid of dead weight,

141
00:06:23,320 --> 00:06:26,080
which was my nickname at school,
and before.

142
00:06:26,120 --> 00:06:29,720
Nannies can be very cruel.

143
00:06:30,560 --> 00:06:32,400
Oh, my God, no.

144
00:06:33,320 --> 00:06:35,960
Marv's choking and I'm not there.

145
00:06:36,120 --> 00:06:39,080
I'm supposed to be the back-patter!

146
00:06:39,280 --> 00:06:42,200
Oh yes, the Putnams
have very narrow esophagi.

147
00:06:42,240 --> 00:06:45,720
The Oregon branch of the family
was completely wiped out

148
00:06:45,760 --> 00:06:50,159
after their wagon train
passed through a cherry farm.

149
00:06:50,200 --> 00:06:51,400
Mm.

150
00:06:53,840 --> 00:06:57,600
- Ken, can I... Can I help you?
- No, I'm good.

151
00:06:57,640 --> 00:07:00,520
And now,
"New Game of the Year."

152
00:07:00,680 --> 00:07:03,760
This award honors a designer
or news organization

153
00:07:03,800 --> 00:07:06,560
for exceptional engagement
in print games.

154
00:07:06,600 --> 00:07:07,600
Come on.

155
00:07:07,680 --> 00:07:11,120
And New Game of the Year goes to...

156
00:07:11,480 --> 00:07:14,000
Oscar Martinez for Mister Digit!

157
00:07:14,040 --> 00:07:16,320
The Toledo Truth Teller.

158
00:07:17,040 --> 00:07:19,160
Hey, it's good!
It's good either way.

159
00:07:19,200 --> 00:07:20,520
- Yeah!
- Don't change.

160
00:07:20,560 --> 00:07:21,640
Don't change, though.

161
00:07:21,680 --> 00:07:23,360
Thank you!

162
00:07:23,560 --> 00:07:25,520
I... I'd be just as proud if he lost.

163
00:07:25,560 --> 00:07:29,640
Oh, my God. Just admit you want
something for once.

164
00:07:29,680 --> 00:07:32,360
You know what?
I want to dedicate...

165
00:07:32,400 --> 00:07:35,920
this win to a group

166
00:07:35,960 --> 00:07:38,000
that doesn't get enough attention,

167
00:07:38,040 --> 00:07:42,040
the documentary film crew
that's been following me around

168
00:07:42,080 --> 00:07:45,120
for the better part of 20 years.

169
00:07:45,159 --> 00:07:49,600
I'm sorry
I pushed you guys away before.

170
00:07:49,880 --> 00:07:52,240
I think you guys are the only
ones who really see me.

171
00:07:53,360 --> 00:07:55,360
And, um...

172
00:07:55,400 --> 00:08:00,880
I guess I was put on earth
to be a documentary subject.

173
00:08:01,160 --> 00:08:03,600
And I never told you guys this

174
00:08:03,640 --> 00:08:06,200
but sometimes I answer, uh,

175
00:08:06,240 --> 00:08:09,120
interview questions in my dreams.

176
00:08:10,080 --> 00:08:11,600
So, there you have that.

177
00:08:11,640 --> 00:08:15,560
And they're playing me out now,
which is pretty cool.

178
00:08:15,600 --> 00:08:17,560
Um... Uh...

179
00:08:17,600 --> 00:08:19,920
I need to thank Marv Putnam.

180
00:08:19,960 --> 00:08:23,080
Marv, thank you

181
00:08:23,120 --> 00:08:25,440
for ignoring the naysayers.

182
00:08:25,480 --> 00:08:27,960
And for believing in us.

183
00:08:30,400 --> 00:08:31,840
Thank you, Marv!

184
00:08:31,880 --> 00:08:34,280
When he says naysayers,
he means me.

185
00:08:35,520 --> 00:08:37,880
I can only see one way out of this.

186
00:08:37,919 --> 00:08:40,080
I need to save Marv's life.

187
00:08:40,120 --> 00:08:41,919
Tonight.

188
00:08:47,200 --> 00:08:50,000
- Your category's up soon.
- Oh, I know.

189
00:08:50,440 --> 00:08:52,760
Unlike you, I'm not pretending
I don't care.

190
00:08:52,800 --> 00:08:56,120
God, it just feels so ridiculous
to even be nominated.

191
00:08:57,920 --> 00:09:01,800
I think it would be ridiculous
if you didn't win.

192
00:09:09,920 --> 00:09:13,120
Don Lye
for "Kroger Wage Violations",

193
00:09:13,880 --> 00:09:17,480
Mare Pritti
for "Softees Clogs Toledo",

194
00:09:17,520 --> 00:09:21,760
Kelcy Fist for ""P" and "G"
A Flood of Green washing",

195
00:09:22,120 --> 00:09:23,400
And Huey Cheang

196
00:09:23,440 --> 00:09:25,720
for "Ohio State Admissions
Explained."

197
00:09:25,760 --> 00:09:27,000
And the winner is...

198
00:09:27,040 --> 00:09:28,720
Mare Pritti for Toledo Truth Teller.

199
00:09:28,760 --> 00:09:30,600
Oh, my God!

200
00:09:30,640 --> 00:09:34,080
Yeah! Yeah! Yeah!
Get over here!

201
00:09:34,120 --> 00:09:35,680
Oh, my God!

202
00:09:40,480 --> 00:09:43,040
Yeah! Whoo!

203
00:09:44,440 --> 00:09:46,200
- We did this together!
- No, we didn't.

204
00:09:46,240 --> 00:09:50,160
- We did this together! Wow!
- No, we didn't.

205
00:09:50,200 --> 00:09:52,800
- Whoo!
- No, no.

206
00:09:53,920 --> 00:09:57,120
Thank you. Oh, my God.

207
00:09:57,160 --> 00:09:58,520
Okay. Um...

208
00:09:58,560 --> 00:10:01,760
When I first started here
at the Toledo Truth Teller,

209
00:10:01,800 --> 00:10:06,480
I wasn't even sure I would write
an article I'd be proud of, heh,

210
00:10:06,520 --> 00:10:08,680
let alone winning an award.

211
00:10:08,720 --> 00:10:10,240
Um... I mean, five months ago,

212
00:10:10,280 --> 00:10:12,600
I was pulling articles off a wire,

213
00:10:12,640 --> 00:10:14,400
ranking the arches
on Love Islanders' feet.

214
00:10:16,720 --> 00:10:18,400
Sorry, my heart is racing so fast.

215
00:10:18,440 --> 00:10:21,120
Okay, I need to thank
my first editor-in-chief,

216
00:10:21,160 --> 00:10:24,160
Sergeant Jones, the only editor
who can make you drop

217
00:10:24,200 --> 00:10:27,680
and give you 50 pushups if you
misuse the word "hopefully."

218
00:10:27,720 --> 00:10:31,360
My high school English teacher,
shout out to Mr. Jenkins.

219
00:10:31,400 --> 00:10:35,640
And finally,
I need to thank Ned Sampson...

220
00:10:35,680 --> 00:10:37,760
our editor-in-chief,

221
00:10:37,800 --> 00:10:39,360
my editor-in-chief.

222
00:10:39,400 --> 00:10:44,520
He gave me an opportunity
that changed my life.

223
00:10:44,640 --> 00:10:48,000
And he tends to do that
with people, so thank you.

224
00:10:48,040 --> 00:10:53,000
All you need to do to make
a dream come true is chase it.

225
00:10:53,040 --> 00:10:55,400
Don't stop chasing.

226
00:10:55,440 --> 00:10:56,920
Thank you, Ned.

227
00:10:56,960 --> 00:10:59,320
I can't wait to celebrate
with you tonight.

228
00:11:04,760 --> 00:11:06,080
That's awesome, Mare.

229
00:11:08,480 --> 00:11:10,960
I can't believe I won
an award for journalism.

230
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:12,560
It's just, uh...

231
00:11:12,600 --> 00:11:14,000
I don't know, it's hard to believe

232
00:11:14,040 --> 00:11:15,360
how hopeful I feel right now.

233
00:11:15,400 --> 00:11:17,920
I feel like, uh,
anything could happen.

234
00:11:17,960 --> 00:11:19,720
Ohio Award!

235
00:11:19,760 --> 00:11:21,880
Theo and I, um,
we go back to seventh grade.

236
00:11:21,920 --> 00:11:25,600
He's a bozo, but we bring
each other to stuff sometimes.

237
00:11:25,640 --> 00:11:27,400
This year, we have felt the loss

238
00:11:27,440 --> 00:11:30,280
of some of Ohio's
most treasured journalists.

239
00:11:30,320 --> 00:11:33,560
Let us take a moment to honor them.

240
00:11:45,760 --> 00:11:48,520
Good evening, my colleagues.

241
00:11:48,560 --> 00:11:50,440
Keep playing, maestro.

242
00:11:51,400 --> 00:11:54,360
My name is Esmeralda Grand,

243
00:11:54,400 --> 00:12:00,400
and I'm so very sad
for all these dead people.

244
00:12:00,920 --> 00:12:03,160
It's so sad to be dead.

245
00:12:03,200 --> 00:12:07,600
'Oh, sad, dead journalist

246
00:12:09,720 --> 00:12:14,280
'You made
Your final deadline'

247
00:12:16,480 --> 00:12:18,280
Oh, yes, please.

248
00:12:18,320 --> 00:12:20,720
Respect to the dead.

249
00:12:21,600 --> 00:12:24,240
'You are gone

250
00:12:24,600 --> 00:12:29,080
'Sad dead journalist
You are gone

251
00:12:29,120 --> 00:12:33,640
'And no one will read you
Anymore'

252
00:12:34,240 --> 00:12:36,400
R.I.P.!

253
00:12:39,240 --> 00:12:41,960
Thank you, thank you, guys.

254
00:12:56,000 --> 00:12:57,640
- Hey, hey, hey.
- Don't, please, don't.

255
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:01,120
You specifically told me that
